    <h1>Professional LG Dryer Igniter Repair Services in Los Angeles</h1>
    <p>Nothing's more frustrating than tossing wet clothes into your LG gas dryer only to find them still damp hours later. Nine times out of ten when we get calls about gas dryers that won't heat, our technicians trace the problem straight back to a failed igniter.</p>
<h2>How to Tell if Your LG Dryer Igniter Has Failed</h2>
<p>Most homeowners don't realize their dryer igniter is the culprit until they've already wasted time checking lint traps and vents. The telltale sign? Your dryer runs through complete cycles but clothes come out cold and soggy. Our techs see this constantly — the igniter glows orange for a few seconds, then dies out without lighting the gas burner. You might hear the dryer running normally, but no heat means no drying. Don't confuse this with a clogged vent, which usually causes overheating shutdowns. A bad igniter lets the dryer run full cycles while producing zero heat.</p>
<h3>Visual Signs Your Igniter is Going Bad</h3>
<p>Our technicians know exactly what to look for during diagnostics. A healthy igniter glows bright orange-white and stays lit long enough to open the gas valve. When igniters start failing, they either won't glow at all or glow weakly for just a few seconds before going dark. Some crack visibly from thermal stress. The first thing our techs check is whether the igniter draws proper amperage — weak igniters might glow but can't pull enough current to trigger the gas valve solenoid.</p>
<h2>Compatible LG Dryer Models for Igniter Replacement</h2>
<p>LG uses several different igniter configurations across their model lines, and using the wrong part guarantees failure. Our techs carry OEM igniters for all major LG series including DLEX, DLGX, and the newer ThinQ smart models. The DLEX3570 and DLGX3571 series use identical igniters, but don't assume compatibility across different series. We've seen DIY attempts go wrong when homeowners ordered generic igniters from big box stores. LG Signature models require specific high-performance igniters that cost more but last longer under the intense heat cycles these premium units generate.</p>
<h3>Why Model-Specific Parts Matter</h3>
<p>Generic igniters might fit physically but won't perform reliably in LG dryers. Our experience shows that aftermarket igniters fail within months because they can't handle LG's specific voltage and amperage requirements. We stock genuine LG igniters because they're engineered for each model's exact specifications. The wrong igniter might work initially but will burn out fast, leaving you right back where you started.</p>
<h2>Professional LG Dryer Igniter Installation Process</h2>
<p>Igniter replacement looks simple until you're face-to-face with gas connections and electrical wiring. Our technicians follow strict safety protocols — gas line shutoff first, then electrical disconnect. The igniter mounts inside the burner assembly, requiring partial disassembly of the dryer's lower section. We test continuity on the new igniter before installation and verify proper gas valve operation afterward. Don't try this repair yourself unless you're comfortable working with gas appliances. One loose connection can create dangerous gas leaks or electrical shorts.</p>
<h3>Testing and Calibration After Installation</h3>
<p>Installing the igniter is only half the job. Our techs run complete test cycles to verify proper ignition timing and gas flow. We check that the igniter glows for the correct duration before the gas valve opens — too short and it won't light, too long and it wastes energy. We also inspect the flame sensor and gas valve solenoid since igniter problems often damage these components too.</p>
<h2>Why OEM LG Igniters Outperform Aftermarket Parts</h2>
<p>We've repaired thousands of LG dryers across LA County and learned the hard way that aftermarket igniters create more problems than they solve. Genuine LG igniters cost about 30% more upfront but last three times longer than generic replacements. The silicon carbide construction in OEM igniters handles thermal cycling better, while cheap alternatives crack from repeated heating and cooling. Our 85% first-visit fix rate depends on using parts that won't fail again in six months. We guarantee OEM igniters for a full year because we know they'll perform reliably.</p>
<h3>Long-Term Cost Comparison</h3>
<p>Homeowners in Burbank and Pasadena often ask about cheaper igniter options, but our techs explain the math clearly. A $40 aftermarket igniter that fails in eight months costs more than a $60 OEM part that lasts five years. Factor in repeat service calls and you're looking at double the total expense. We only stock genuine LG parts because our customers deserve repairs that actually solve the problem permanently.</p>
<h2>When Igniter Problems Indicate Bigger Issues</h2>
<p>Sometimes a failed igniter reveals deeper problems with your LG dryer's gas system. Our technicians frequently find that repeated igniter failures stem from faulty gas valve solenoids or blocked burner tubes. If your igniter has failed multiple times, don't just replace it again — there's usually an underlying cause. We perform complete combustion system diagnostics to identify why igniters keep burning out. Restricted airflow from clogged vents can also overheat igniters and cause premature failure.</p>
<h3>Comprehensive Gas System Inspection</h3>
<p>Our diagnostic process goes beyond just checking the igniter. We test gas pressure, inspect flame sensors, and verify proper ventilation. Many igniter problems in Orange County homes trace back to lint buildup restricting exhaust flow, which creates excessive heat in the combustion chamber. A thorough inspection prevents repeat failures and ensures your dryer operates safely and efficiently.</p>

<h2>Frequently Asked Questions</h2>
<h3>How do I know if my LG dryer igniter is bad?</h3>
<p>The most obvious sign is when your dryer runs complete cycles but clothes come out cold and wet. You might see the igniter glow orange briefly through the front panel, then go dark without lighting the gas burner. Our techs also check if the igniter draws proper amperage — weak igniters can't generate enough current to open the gas valve even if they glow.</p>
<h3>What LG dryer models use the same igniter part?</h3>
<p>Many DLEX and DLGX series models share identical igniters, but don't assume compatibility across different series. LG ThinQ and Signature models typically require specific igniters. Our technicians verify the exact part number from your model's service manual rather than guessing based on visual similarity. Using the wrong igniter guarantees early failure.</p>
<h3>Can I replace an LG dryer igniter myself?</h3>
<p>We don't recommend DIY igniter replacement unless you're experienced with gas appliances. The repair involves disconnecting gas lines and accessing the burner assembly inside the dryer. One mistake can create gas leaks or damage other components. Our techs also test the entire combustion system after replacement to ensure everything works safely together.</p>
<h3>How much does an LG dryer igniter replacement cost?</h3>
<p>Our igniter replacement service typically runs $150-220 including the genuine LG part and labor. We charge a $65 diagnostic fee upfront, but waive it when you proceed with the repair. The total cost depends on your specific LG model and whether we find any related issues with the gas valve or flame sensor during our inspection.</p>
<h3>Where can I buy genuine LG dryer igniter parts?</h3>
<p>We stock OEM LG igniters for all major models and can install them same-day in most cases. You can order parts directly from LG or appliance parts suppliers, but make sure you get the exact part number for your model. Generic igniters from big box stores might fit but won't last as long as genuine LG parts designed for your specific dryer.</p>
